        <body>
            <head>Sample Math Encoding Article</head>
            <div>
                <head>ASCIIMath examples</head>
                <!-- Include the ` delimiter to open and close the ASCIIMath content within each <formula> element.
                     Use @rend with "inline" or "block" to indicate the display handling of the code.                
                -->
                <p>Samples of ASCIIMath encoding. When <formula notation="asciimath" rend="inline"
                        >`a != 0`</formula>, there are two solutions to <formula
                        notation="asciimath" rend="inline">`ax^2 + bx + c = 0`</formula> and they
                    are <formula notation="asciimath" rend="block">`x = (-b +- sqrt(b^2-4ac))/(2a).`</formula>
                </p>

            </div>



            <div>
                <head>TeX examples</head>
                <!-- Include the \( and \) delimiters to open and close inline TeX content within each <formula> element.
                     Include the $$ delimiter to open and close block-level TeX content within the <formula> element.
                     Use @rend with "inline" or "block" to indicate the display handling of the code.                
                -->
                
                
                <p>Sample of TeX encoding: When <formula notation="tex" rend="inline">\(a \ne
                        0\)</formula>, there are two solutions to <formula notation="tex"
                        rend="inline">\(ax^2 + bx + c = 0\)</formula>, and they are <formula
                        notation="tex" rend="block">$$x = {-b \pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac} \over 2a}.$$</formula> Furthermore, Einstein proved decisively that the
                    relationship between energy and mass involves the speed of light, following the
                    formula <formula notation="tex" rend="inline">\(E=mc^2\)</formula>. I have no
                    idea what these next examples prove, but I'm sure it's important: <formula
                        notation="tex" rend="block">$$ {1 \over 10} + {1 \over 100} + {1 \over 1000}
                        + {1 \over 10,\!000} + \dots $$</formula> I also think we should not have
                    periods following block-level formulae. This one seems especially interesting:
                        <formula notation="tex" rend="block">$$\matrix{0 &amp;amp;
                        1\cr&amp;lt;0&amp;amp;>1}$$</formula>
                </p>



            </div>
            <div>
                <head>Examples/validation tests of MathML</head>
                   <p>After constructing a random walk process from the time series, the
                            initial step of AFA involves partitioning the time series into
                            overlapping segments of length <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math
                                xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">w</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">=</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">2</mn><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">n</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">+</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">1</mn></mml:math></formula>, in
                            which neighboring segments overlap by <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math
                                xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">n</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">+</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">1</mn></mml:math></formula>
                            points. In each segment, the time series is fitted with the best
                            polynomial of order <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math
                                xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">M</mi></mml:math></formula>,
                            obtained using standard least-squares regression. The fitted polynomials
                            in overlapped regions are then combined to yield a single global
                            smoothed trend. Denoting the fitted polynomials for the <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math
                                xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">i</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">-</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">t</mi><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">h</mi></mml:math></formula> and
                                <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">i</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">+</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">1</mn><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">-</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">t</mi><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">h</mi></mml:math></formula>
                            segments by <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                    ><msup xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                            ><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></msup><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><msub
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo></mml:math></formula> and
                                <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></msup><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><msub
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo></mml:math></formula>,
                            respectively, where <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math
                                xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">,</mo><msub
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">=</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">1</mn><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">,</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">⋯</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">,</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">2</mn><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">n</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">+</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">1</mn></mml:math></formula>, we
                            define the fitting for the overlapped region as</p>
                        <p><formula rend="block" notation="mathml"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msup><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">l</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">=</mo><msub
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msup
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msup><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">l</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">+</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">n</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">+</mo><msub
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msup
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></msup><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">l</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">,</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"> </mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"> </mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">l</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">=</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">1,2</mn><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">,</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">⋯</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">,</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">n</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">+</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">1</mn><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">,</mo></mml:math></formula>
                        where <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">=</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">1</mn><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">-</mo><mfrac
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                            ><mrow><mi>l</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo></mml:math></formula> and
                                <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">=</mo><mfrac
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                            ><mrow><mi>l</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></mfrac></mml:math></formula>
                            can be written as <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math
                                xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">1</mn><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">-</mo><msub
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">/</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">n</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo></mml:math></formula> for
                                <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">j</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">=</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">1,2</mn></mml:math></formula>,
                            and where <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mml:math></formula>
                            denotes the distances between the point and the centers of <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math
                                xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msup></mml:math></formula>
                            and <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></msup></mml:math></formula>,
                            respectively. Note that the weights decrease linearly with the distance
                            between the point and the center of the segment. Such a weighting is
                            used to ensure symmetry and to effectively eliminate any jumps or
                            discontinuities around the boundaries of neighboring segments. As a
                            result, the global trend is smooth at the non-boundary points and it has
                            the right and left derivatives at the boundary <ptr target="#riley2012"
                            />.</p>
                        <p>The global trend can be used to maximally suppress the effect of complex
                            nonlinear trends on the scaling analysis. The parameters of each local
                            fit are determined by maximizing the goodness of fit in each segment.
                            The different polynomials in the overlapped part of each segment are
                            combined such that the global fit will be the smoothest fit of the
                            overall time series. Even if the local fits are linear, <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math
                                xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">M</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">=</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">1</mn></mml:math></formula>,
                            the global trend signal will still be nonlinear. AFA then can be
                            described accordingly: for an arbitrary window size <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math
                                xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">w</mi></mml:math></formula>, we
                            determine, for the random walk process <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math
                                xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">u</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">i</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo></mml:math></formula>, a
                            global trend <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                    ><mi xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">v</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">i</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">,</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">i</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">=</mo><mn
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">1,2</mn><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">,</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">⋯</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">,</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">N</mi></mml:math></formula>,
                            where <formula notation="mathml" rend="inline"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">N</mi></mml:math></formula> is
                            the length of the walk. The residual of the fit, <formula rend="inline" notation="mathml"><mml:math
                                xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">u</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">i</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">-</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">v</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">i</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo></mml:math></formula>,
                            characterizes fluctuations around the global trend, and its variance
                            yields the Hurst exponent <formula rend="inline" notation="mathml"><mml:math
                                xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">H</mi></mml:math></formula>
                            according to the following scaling equation:</p>
                        <p><formula notation="mathml" rend="block"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">F</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">w</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">=</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">[</mo><mfrac
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow></mfrac><munderover
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                            ><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow></munderover><mrow
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>(</mo></mrow><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">u</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">i</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">-</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">v</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">i</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo><msup
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><msup
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mo>]</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">∼</mo><msup
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                        ><mrow><mi>w</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow></msup><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">.</mo></mml:math></formula></p>
                        <p>By computing the global fits, the residual, and the variance between
                            original random walk process and the fitted trend for each window size
                                <formula rend="inline" notation="mathml"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">w</mi></mml:math></formula>, we
                            can plot <formula rend="inline" notation="mathml"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                            ><mrow><mtext>log</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">F</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">(</mo><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">w</mi><mo
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">)</mo></mml:math></formula> as
                            a function of <formula rend="inline" notation="mathml"><mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                    ><msub xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
                                            ><mrow><mtext>log</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">w</mi></mml:math></formula>.
                            The presence of fractal scaling amounts to a linear relation in the
                            plot, with the slope of the relation providing an estimate of <formula rend="inline" notation="mathml"><mml:math
                                xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi
                                    xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">H</mi></mml:math></formula>
                            (see Figure <ref target="#figure01">1</ref>).</p>
